This is more geared to freelancer types and start-ups (hipster like).

E.g. in most real jobs: 
The security responsibility is not true. It's a speciality, and highly complex to keep up with, or know how to test on it (e.g. pen tests, white-hat hacking). NEVER let developers be in charge of this.
Server maintenance isn't one either, it's for sysadmins to do. (a properly operated business has speciality dividing by roles: sysadmins, netadmins, security department, backend dev, frontend dev, project leads, management, DB engineers/admins, cloud engineers, etc etc etc) Each role knows their field of expertise, don't become a jack of all trades, but a master of none type of person.

As a backend developer you don't need to know much (in detail): version control, projectmanagement (Lean, Agile, Scrum etc), The language used ofcourse!, some concepts like REST/GraphQL, Database types, Scaling in general. But the rest is a speciality concern: e.g. DB optimizations, High availablitiy setups, Security etc etc etc.
Do not ever touch JavaScript. Especially, for the backend development this is madness.
JavaScript should only be used inside browser 😂

A word of advice to aspiring young programmers who might be overwhelmed with that list. In my personal experience, the only thing you need to know is programming \\ but know it well. That's what you should focus on. The rest is secondary, technologies and tools come and go. Along the way you will learn other things as you need them.

🎯 Key Takeaways for quick navigation:

00:00 *🛠️ Technologies Needed for Backend Development*
- Backend development defined as creating logic and server-side software for websites and applications.
- Responsibilities of backend developers: server-side logic, database management, API development, server management, security.
- Becoming a backend developer involves mastering programming languages, database management, and server management, along with continuous learning and community engagement.
03:11 *🌐 Understanding Internet Basics for Backend Development*
- Importance of understanding how data is transmitted over the internet, DNS functionality, and HTTP/HTTPS protocols.
- Solid grasp of internet fundamentals enhances backend developers' ability to build efficient and secure applications.
03:53 *💻 Programming Languages for Backend Development*
- JavaScript and its use in backend development with Node.js for scalability.
- Python's readability and efficiency, supported by frameworks like Django and Flask.
- Other languages commonly used for backend development include PHP and Java.
04:34 *📝 Version Control and Collaboration*
- Git as a version control system for tracking and managing code changes.
- GitHub's role in facilitating collaboration, code review, and project management.
- Understanding Git and GitHub essential for maintaining code integrity and collaborating effectively.
05:00 *🗃️ Relational Database Management Systems*
- Importance of relational database management systems (RDBMS) like MySQL, PostgreSQL, or Oracle.
- Vital role of backend developers in designing, querying, and managing data efficiently within RDBMS.
- Ensuring data integrity and performance is a key aspect of backend development.
06:07 *🔒 API Security and Testing*
- Paramount importance of API security for protecting sensitive data and preventing unauthorized access.
- Testing methodologies, including unit testing, integration testing, and end-to-end testing, to ensure code reliability and functionality.
- Implementing security measures such as authentication, authorization, data encryption, and regular audits essential for API security.
06:50 *🏗️ Software Design and Architecture*
- Crucial role of understanding software design and architecture in creating scalable and efficient backend systems.
- Knowledge of design patterns, architectural styles, and principles for better performance and scalability.
- Message brokers like RabbitMQ and Kafka for facilitating communication in distributed systems.
07:16 *📦 Containerization Technologies*
- Essential role of Docker and Kubernetes in creating, deploying, and managing applications in isolated, scalable environments.
- Docker for packaging applications into containers, Kubernetes for orchestrating container lifecycle.
- Importance of containerization for enhancing application consistency and scalability.
07:45 *🔄 GraphQL and MongoDB*
- GraphQL's efficiency in requesting specific data in APIs, offering an alternative to traditional REST APIs.
- MongoDB's NoSQL database, suitable for fast querying, scalability, and handling diverse data types.
- Firebase's suite of tools for rapid development and scalability, particularly favored for startups and agile projects.
09:16 *🌐 Infrastructure and Cloud Services*
- Understanding server, network, and cloud infrastructure crucial for backend developers.
- Familiarity with cloud providers like AWS, Azure, or Google Cloud, and services like virtual machines and serverless computing enhances efficiency and scalability.
- Continuous adaptation to new technologies and best practices essential for success in backend development.

At around 6:41 I am getting a deprecation warning about the usage of: useNewUrlParser.  Does anyone know what I should be using instead?  Thankyou and Regards.

@6:41:40 after four days of typing the code and another 3 days of trying to debug the code - I finally got the database to accept an entry.  Now, I am going to lay my weary head to rest, and I won't cry no more.  That was an ordeal of great magnitude.  This part of the course was not structured well, and while I finally got to grips with what the code was doing and can understand it in part, I did not "LEARN" how I would use it in a project I create - it would've been far better to 1. learn how to set up the database - 2. then place a single entry.   Then 3, after that read the entry back.  4. update it - doing each section in sections testing and debugging as we went along.  Really getting to grips with the very basics on using an online database before doing anything else.  Rather than being hit over the head with a completed solution that we just type in and hope there are not too many errors. This would give us bite sized chunks of code and checkpoints to test code making it far easier to debug - at one point I was about to give up because nothing was going through to the database it wasn't until I saw the errors pop up on the console when I stopped the code running that I had a chance - up to that point everything was saying it was a success and nothing was going to the database.  That how I would handle this lesson but what would I know, I am just an Instructor in Martial arts.  I was rather disappointed with this section after a superb section on JavaScript - even that lesson would've been better breaking it into smaller sections to avoid that dreaded parser error in line 57.  Also the deprecation warning took me aback how long will it be before the useNewUrlParser fails to work?  Leaving the course broken.  Does anyone know what I should use instead?

Overall i think this is a nice tutorial. Although in my opinion many important aspects do not get explained pretty good by Tomi. Some code is just written down without further explanation and there are also some parts that are written in a weird or unpractical style. For example: I would have loved to see how this API setup is really working and set up in the background. The API request we set up returns an object that contains all the movies with all the properties and you can see all of that in the console when we print the object. This would've made it much easier to understand, where the properties come from that you just copy pasted. Also an explanation where the API constants are found on the Website (APILINK, IMG_PATH, etc.). I eventually figured it all out by myself, which is fine though, but this way many people won't be able to reproduce this by their own. I think this tutorial is still good, i just wanted to point that out, because i haven't seen anyone complain about it. Keep it up.

### Resumo
Este conteúdo é um tutorial em vídeo do YouTube sobre Python para iniciantes, apresentado por Dave Gray. O curso destaca-se por incluir uma série de pequenos projetos práticos que ajudam os alunos a compreender os recursos-chave do Python. Ele está dividido em 23 capítulos bem definidos e é elogiado pela clareza e experiência de ensino de Dave Gray. O vídeo também aborda por que aprender Python é uma escolha sólida devido à sua simplicidade, versatilidade, grande comunidade de usuários e oportunidades de trabalho.

### Destaques
- 🐍 O curso apresentado por Dave Gray é voltado para iniciantes e inclui projetos práticos.
- 📘 O curso é dividido em 23 capítulos bem definidos, organizados como um livro de vídeo.
- 🎓 Python é elogiado por sua simplicidade, versatilidade e grande comunidade de usuários.
- 💼 A linguagem Python oferece boas oportunidades de emprego devido à sua popularidade.
- 🖥 Os espectadores são orientados a configurar um ambiente Python no Visual Studio Code e a usar a formatação automática para facilitar o desenvolvimento.

At 1:27, the problem is that you enter an incorrect value for price, then submit the form. This reloads the page and reloading the page makes the file upload 'forget' the selected image file. Then you fix the incorrect price value and submit again but this time (as described before) there's no image selected because the form 'forgot' the one you entered before.

This shows a design flaw with the page - it should display an error if no image has been selected, or it should account for the user not selecting an image (maybe by displaying a default image if the item does not have an image).

I like the slow tutorial, so you can follow it. But sadly there are a lot of wrong expaination. It is a good practice to understand the topic, if you are explaining it.
Some examples: 
1. "la" is not a command on a mac it is just an alias probably added with "Oh my zsh!", you can create your own aliases in in UNIX like Os very easy, type "alias --help" to get more information about it.
2. "Because it's blue it means it's a folder" This is in hers situation right because she uses "Oh my zsh!" with this kind of theme there are a lot of different themes for "Oh my zsh!" by the way you can also beautify your bash with "Oh my bash!" but for everyone else: if you use "ls -l" you will get the content of a folder and if the first sighn in the line is a "d" so it is a directory, you can learn more about ls just type: "man ls"
3. ssh key: you email don't need to be the same you just need the key... you can learn more about ssh-keygen just type: "man ssh-keygen"
By the way you should learn as first to use the man pages type "man man" to learn more. man pages are documentation about programs or functions. Not every program has a page in man pages but a lot of them. you can even search in terminal for a program|command just type "apropos <what you searching for>"

FWIW, 

git add vs git commit
----------------------------------
- "git add" sends a modified file in your working repository to the staging area; files are NOT committed
- "git commit" saves files from the staging area; takes a snapshot of your repository's current state, and creates a new revision with a log. each version has a unique identifier.

commit vs push
--------------------------
- commit only saves files locally 
- push sends committed (saved) files to a [specified] remote repository

working directory --> staging area --> local repository --> remote repository
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
working directory files are sent to the staging area via "git add". 
staging area files are added and saved to your local repository via "git commit".
local repository files are added to a remote repository via "git push".

Hey guys, if anyone see a ".DS_Store" file when you commit (with mac) , be careful! Usually this doesn't show when you have a ".gitignore" file set to ignore it in you app's folder. Probably Gwen turned off the automatic creation of this file globally in her terminal by running: defaults write com.apple.desktopservices DSDontWriteNetworkStores true

You can turn it back on by running: defaults write com.apple.desktopservices DSDontWriteNetworkStores false

I feel so relived; I'm finally learning this darn thing! Thank you for the tutorial. Thank you for taking the time to do this Gwen!

Edit: Upon reviewing the tutorial again, I'd like to say:

1. When creating a tutorial, you guys should _truly_ understand the importance of slowing down to the pace of the learner. In the beginning you walk us through a nice set of key terms (which was exceptional), then start mixing lots of advanced and beginner-level concepts together in your explanations, confusing the person that's watching the video. Slow down, explain like we're 5, that's why we're here.

2. To expand upon the issue of mixing things up I mentioned above, it's okay to keep a tutorial short, and add footnotes later if you think that the advanced concepts you're touching on are still worth being aware of. That way, the beginner can truly focus their attention on the basics, and then access the footnote only when they feel comfortable with the knowledge they've acquired thus far, making the content of your footnotes even more effective. After all, isn't good programming about being efficient? 

I used to get annoyed at being expected to take additional English classes as a Computer Science student, but now I understand why. I spent 4 hours yesterday debugging a Terminal issue, only to later realize that there was an "issue" because the person who created the how-to GitHub document instructed the reader to paste this code into the Terminal command line: 

*eval "$(ssh-agent exec -s)"*

They said to *paste* this command in the terminal (meaning: include the quotation marks). After 4 hours of learning about chmod, File Links, Groups, root directory, Inodes—things I knew NOTHING about prior to this, I resolved my problem by simply removing the quotation marks. 

Now, the arrogant developer might say, "Well that's obvious". No it's not! The person said "paste", meaning I would: 

- Select the piece of code
- Apply ctrl+c to it, for Windows (cmd+c on Mac)
- Go to the Terminal and apply ctrl+v/cmd+v

Either the tutorial should have been made like this: 

*eval $(ssh-agent exec -s)* ,  

or the person writing the document should I mentioned that the quotation marks need to be removed. 

As Software Engineering becomes more collaborative, programmers can no longer get away with being asocial, and communication impaired, so this is an area a lot more engineers need to start being proficient in .

So I followed instruction from stackoverflow - to correctly set PATH in Windows 10 to point at Git installation:

1. Go to My Computer => Local Disk(C:) => Program Files => Git => cmd
2. Right Click the git => Select Properties and copy cmd path location
3. Come back and in the Start Menu or taskbar search, search for "environment variable".
4. Select "Edit the system environment variables".
5. Click the "Environment Variables" button at the bottom.
6. Double-click the "Path" entry under "System variables".
7. With the "New" button in the PATH editor, add previously copied CMD path to the end of the list.
8. Press OK
9. Close and re-open your command prompt.


Easy way to avoid messing with PATH variables in the first place is to re-install Git 
and select "Use Git from the Windows Command Prompt" 
(NOT "Use Git from Git Bash only")

Private keys don't generate public keys.  They are mathematically related to each other at creation.  It is extremely difficult to determine the mathmatical relationship, as that seed is destroyed during key creation; however, if you have both keys it is simple to solve.  The simplest explanation that everyone can understand is "You can only read messages encrypted with one key using the other key.  Because everyone has access to the public key, everyone can read messages encrypted with the private key.  Conversely, a message encrypted using the public key can only be read by someone who has the private key.  That's why it is critical to keep private keys secure."

Heads up for anyone doing the step shown in 29:36 (git push origin master). Aside from the fact that (as of the date that I'm writting this) "master" has been renamed to "main", in order to push from a local repository to github, an extra step has been added. It looks like one must now specify (explicitly) on which branch it's located (in this case "main"). So, now, the total steps to follow, for this particular case, would be:

git remote add origin git@github.com:Username/Repository_Name.git
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main

Otherwise (at least in my case) an error appears. With that extra line of code it works fine.

Windows users using VS Code might have their default terminal set to powershell and might have trouble showing hidden folders, like at 16:00. However, command prompt or git bash will allow you to show hidden folders. One way that I did this is by changing the default terminal in VS Code to command prompt. In terminal view, click on the drop down menu and click on "Select Default shell" then choose "Command Prompt" or "Git Bash".

You can add the following code to your settings.json file: "terminal.integrated.shell.windows": "cmd.exe". This will make the default terminal command prompt. If using the command prompt, you can show all visible and hidden files or folders with the command following: dir /a

Really love this git and github intro course, it really touches a lot of things.
1. How to create a repo locally through the CLI(Command Line Interface) or directly from GITHUB
2. git flow by using the most common commands: git add - git commit and git push/git pull, all of them with their corresponding explanation. What "origin", "remote" and "master" mean.
3. git branching: all the commands involve in that kind of operation as well as best practices.
4. git merging: when we use a "feature" branch and it's time to merge to the "master" branch  -- PR (Pull Request) on the Github side
5. How to deal with "conflicts" when merging.
6. Undoing in git: undoing from the stage area versus undoing if we have committed once or several times.
7. Understanding how and why we fork a repo on github.

🎯 Key Takeaways for quick navigation:

00:00 *🎓 Craig Dennis offers an updated, beginner-friendly API course taught by an experienced developer educator.*
00:29 *💻 The course assumes basic coding knowledge and familiarity with web concepts but starts from the ground up, covering what APIs are, why they exist, and their benefits.*
03:22 *🔍 The course begins by breaking down the term "API" and its significance, then delves into hands-on experience with web APIs.*
04:17 *📱 Learners will build a web application utilizing existing APIs, focusing solely on using APIs rather than creating them.*
08:42 *🌐 APIs serve as contracts, defining usage expectations and facilitating communication between software components, locally and remotely.*
20:37 *📄 HTTP requests and responses contain crucial information like headers, status codes, and content type, facilitating effective communication between clients and servers.*
23:03 *🌐 Understanding basic concepts like HTTP and statelessness is crucial for comprehending RESTful APIs, which build upon these principles to expose and manipulate resources.*
24:59 *🔄 REST APIs follow client-server architecture and are stateless, requiring clients to maintain session details and send them with each request, adhering to REST constraints.*
26:57 *🔍 Resources in REST APIs are abstract entities representing objects like books or photos, with CRUD operations (Create, Read, Update, Delete) commonly performed on them.*
28:23 *🛠️ RESTful APIs allow interaction with various applications via HTTP methods, enabling data retrieval, task automation, and integration of different services for versatile functionality.*
38:28 *🎵 When interacting with APIs, it's crucial to protect sensitive information like OAuth tokens to prevent unauthorized access to your account.*
39:28 *🎤 APIs like Spotify's offer various functionalities, allowing users to search for artists, retrieve information about them, and access their music libraries.*
42:58 *🏃‍♂️ Exploring APIs opens up opportunities for innovative app ideas, such as a music festival app that suggests bands based on users' listening habits.*
45:13 *🛠️ Transitioning from exploring APIs on websites to making requests using tools like Curl provides hands-on experience and deeper understanding.*
50:12 *🔄 Navigating APIs through URLs and using tools like JQ for data parsing empowers developers to interact more efficiently and effectively with API endpoints.*
55:44 *🎤 APIs like Spotify often use Curl in their documentation to demonstrate usage.*
56:12 *📱 Twilio offers APIs for various communication channels like SMS, calls, and emails, making it versatile for developers.*
57:42 *🛡️ Twilio's APIs abstract away complexities, enabling developers to send text messages with a single command without needing to understand underlying infrastructure.*
58:11 *💼 Signing up for Twilio's trial account provides access to its APIs without requiring a credit card.*
01:00:25 *🌐 Twilio's developer-friendly interface allows users to choose coding language preferences and provides serverless hosting options.*
01:03:52 *🔑 Twilio trial accounts have limitations, such as only allowing messages and calls to verified numbers.*
01:12:50 *🧼 Using JQ can make JSON responses from APIs more readable and organized, though it's optional.*
01:13:46 *🛠️ Start exploring APIs visually with tools like Postman, which offer user-friendly interfaces and features.*
01:15:24 *🕹️ Explore API documentation and interact with APIs using tools similar to Postman, like REST Fox, for easier experimentation.*
01:17:57 *📁 Organize API requests by grouping them in folders within tools like REST Fox, facilitating navigation and management.*
01:27:49 *📩 Adjust API requests, such as switching between GET and POST methods, and configure parameters like headers and body data for specific functionalities.*
01:30:47 *📱 When using Twilio for sending messages via REST API, authentication with username and password is essential, and media URLs can be included in the message body.*
01:32:15 *🛠️ Setting up environments in REST clients like Postman or REST Fox helps avoid duplication of authentication credentials and allows for easy management of variables like account SID and auth token.*
01:35:12 *🔄 Environment variables in REST clients allow for easy sharing and modification of sensitive information like phone numbers and authentication tokens across requests.*
01:49:16 *🛠️ Helper libraries or SDKs specific to programming languages help make code more concise, readable, and offer additional documentation support within editors.*
01:53:06 *💻 Setting up environment variables and installing necessary libraries are essential steps when working with APIs and helper libraries in local development environments.*
02:06:12 *🔄 By using the `await` keyword, asynchronous functions can be written more clearly, allowing for synchronous-like execution flow.*
02:09:32 *🚫 Incorrect function name errors can be caught and rectified, ensuring proper execution of code.*
02:10:33 *🧹 Removing messages from an API involves calling a method on the message object, which initiates a delete request via a REST API call.*
02:12:53 *🔄 Helper libraries for various programming languages provide a consistent and standardized approach to interacting with APIs, maintaining uniformity across different languages.*
02:14:49 *⌨️ Command-line interfaces (CLIs) offer a convenient tool for making API calls directly from an executable on your machine, commonly used for automation tasks or interacting with cloud services.*
02:15:46 *🌐 Integrating helper libraries within applications simplifies API usage and enhances functionality, enabling tasks like batch scripting or automation.*
02:16:16 *🛠️ Building web applications that interact with external APIs can be achieved even without extensive coding knowledge, focusing on integrating APIs into existing frameworks.*
02:23:29 *☁️ Deploying web applications has become easier with serverless technology, eliminating the need for managing physical servers and infrastructure, and providing scalability and reliability.*
02:24:27 *🌐 Twilio can host web applications using its serverless environment, allowing developers to serve HTML without managing traditional web servers.*
02:25:54 *📄 Functions in Twilio are commonly used to power applications, including handling responses to incoming messages, and can be edited in an integrated development environment provided by Twilio.*
02:26:58 *⚙️ Serverless solutions like Twilio handle scalability concerns, allowing developers to focus on building applications without worrying about infrastructure management.*
02:33:25 *📩 Developers can use Twilio's helper libraries and TwiML (Twilio Markup Language) to construct and return structured responses to incoming messages.*
02:36:53 *🌐 With the ability to host applications, developers can design and implement custom APIs using Twilio functions, simplifying the integration process for front-end developers.*
02:40:17 *🖥️ Twilio functions allow developers to create APIs easily, with the ability to automatically return JSON responses based on the provided data.*
02:43:10 *🛠️ JavaScript code to access Twilio REST client allows authentication using context object with account SID and Auth token, providing access to Twilio services within a function.*
02:44:48 *📞 Environment variables can be used to securely store sensitive information like Twilio credentials, enhancing code readability and security.*
02:48:43 *🖼️ Dynamically populating an array with image URLs and descriptions retrieved from Twilio messages, ensuring proper formatting for display.*
02:51:07 *🌐 Explanation of shaping data from API responses to match desired format for client applications, highlighting the importance of data formatting and accessibility considerations.*
02:57:18 *🍽️ Integration of server-based API with client-side application using web API Fetch to retrieve data from the server, demonstrating the practical application of APIs in web development.*
03:00:40 *🌐 APIs can be accessed with minimal lines of code, highlighting the simplicity and power of API integration for retrieving user-generated content.*

for those wondering what was that on 10:22:

it's in ruby language, 
chr(ord('y') ^ 0x20):

1. ord('y') : The `ord` method in Ruby returns the ASCII code of the character passed to it. In this case, `ord('y')` returns the ASCII code for the character 'y', which is 121.

2. 0x20 : This represents the hexadecimal value 20, which is equivalent to 32 in decimal.

3. `^` (XOR operator): The XOR (exclusive OR) operator performs a bitwise XOR operation on the binary representations of two numbers.

4. ord('y') ^ 0x20 This bitwise XOR operation is performed between the ASCII code of 'y' (121 in decimal) and 32. The result is 89.

5. chr(89):  The `chr` method in Ruby converts an ASCII code to its corresponding character. In this case, `chr(89)` returns the character with the ASCII code 89, which is 'Y'.

So, the overall expression `chr(ord('y') ^ 0x20)` takes the character 'y', performs a bitwise XOR with 32, resulting in the ASCII code 89, and then converts that ASCII code back to the character 'Y'.

I learned about this concept in school but it was only briefly covered in a database class and I never understood the point of it until my last job. They were manually configuring hundreds of appliance-type devices through their web UI's which took hours of work. One small change request was many more hours of work again. I realized that these appliances had an API and we were able to reduce hours of work into minutes by writing scripts that took a list of IP's and sent API commands to each device in the list. I did the same thing on another project and cut my estimated completion time in half. 

As someone who is in IT but is not a developer, even I could see the enormous power and potential of the API. It opens the door to automation, which reduces human error dramatically. It also speeds up onboarding. I am looking forward to watching this course and learning more about API's and their other uses.

Second pydantic BaseSettings was not working, so I had to pip install pydantic-settings and make config.py following:

from pydantic_settings import BaseSettings, SettingsConfigDict

class Settings(BaseSettings):
    database_hostname: str
    database_portt: str
    database_password: str
    database_username: str
    database_name: str
    secret_key: str
    algorithm: str
    access_token_expire_minutes: int

    model_config = SettingsConfigDict(env_file=".env")

settings = Settings()

Hope it helps to anyone who had similar problems.

    title: str

4:23:59 cursor.execute("""SELECT * FROM posts WHERE id = %s""", (id)) assumes anything within the 2nd set of brackets to be iterable, so it assume id has an iterable datatype. str() and int() are not iterables, which is why an error is returned, the error being something similar to:
TypeError: query parameters should be a sequence or a mapping, got str/int

Adding a comma and making it (id,) makes all data within the brackets iterable, and allows you to index into the first element id in that iterable sequence.

at 4:24:06, if someone is wondering why we need an additional comma "," after (str(id)) like (str(id),), here is the explanation:

in python the syntax to create a tuple is (ele,) when we have only one element named ele and not (ele)

please check the output of the following:

t = (1)
print(type(t))  # o/p: <class 'int'>

t = (1,)
print(type(t)) # o/p: <class 'tuple'>

At 13:55:05 for those who wondering what causing the Internal server error. In the postgres docker container the tables are not creating, so we need to create the tables in order perform the requested action on localhost:8000.
Follow these steps it has worked for me
1) Put the command docker ps and find your container ID
2) Then enter into the bash -> docker exec -t YOUR_CONTAINER_ID bash
3) Now it will enter into the bash, type -> alembic upgrade head
This will fix the issue by creating the tables to perform the action. Now go to Postman API and run the create user request, it will work. But the only issue is the data is not storing.

for those of you who are still getting an error at 10:22:17 like:
TypeError('cannot convert dictionary update sequence element #0 to a sequence')
try to add this line of code before returning results:
results = list ( map (lambda x : x._mapping, results) )
When querying the db with two arguments in the .query method, sqlalchemy returns a list of sqlalchemy.engine.row.Row objects. As far as I have acknowledged from the documentation:
"Changed in version 1.4:
Renamed RowProxy to .Row. .Row is no longer a "proxy" object in that it contains the final form of data within it, and now acts mostly like a named tuple. Mapping-like functionality is moved to the .Row._mapping attribute, but will remain available in SQLAlchemy 1.x ... "
So, in my understanding, we are not allowed to retrieve the jsonized data directly from the query anymore; the ._mapping method takes care of building the dict structure with "Post" and "votes" keys, and using map does this for each .Row element in the list; we then convert map to a list to be able to return it. 
Please feel free to correct me if I'm wrong, or if you have any better workaround.

If you are watching this after Jan 2023, and you install SQLAlchemy using the pip install command, it will install version 2.0.x or above by default. The code at the 10:25:00 hr marker where you get count is incompatible with the new version of SQLAlchemy.
I spent a few hours figuring out why my exact same code isn't working.
Use the following command to install (or re-install) to a compatible version of SQLAlchemy
pip install --force-reinstall -v "SQLAlchemy==1.4.46"

Also, your PostOut pydantic schema should derive from BaseModel, not Post or PostBase.

I want to clarify the issue that is happening at 4:23:45. 
The cursor.execute() method takes an iterable object as its 2nd argument(like list, tuple, string, etc.), because internally the function loops through the values passed in 2nd argument, to place them into the "%s" placeholders of the 1st argument. Now, when we write like this :- (id) or like (2), because of only single value, it is considered as integer, and not a tuple even parenthesis are used. 
But if we just put a comma and make it like this:- (id,) or (2,), it is indicative of multiple values, and now the object is a tuple, which is an iterable.

Here, we actually do not need the string conversion that is being shown here as cursor.execute(...,str(id)), and we can simply do it as cursor.execute(... , (id,)). It is better actually.

I did some digging in the psycopg2 implementation and I think I have an explanation that ties together what you're addressing at 4:21:33 and 4:23:36. 

TLDR: Always use a 'sequence' like tuples, lists, and so on for the second parameter of cursor.execute(). For tuples with a single object, write '(object, )' instead of '(object)'. 

Firstly, we should look at some signatures.

The execute method for cursor objects:
def execute(self, query: str | bytes | Composable, vars: _Vars = ...) -> None: ...

The _Vars type alias:
_Vars: TypeAlias = Sequence[Any] | Mapping[str, Any] | None

These explain what makes the 'convert to str' workaround tick. But as you've demonstrated before while writing the create_posts function, you can pass non-string values (e.g., bools in the case of post.published) just fine. So, why wasn't '(id)' working? I think this is because of the weird syntax of Python's tuples. '(id)' is not necessarily a tuple, and therefore not a sequence either. But '(id, )' is always a tuple in Python, and so it works just fine. But when you're forcing it to be a tuple with that extra comma, your previous workaround of converting to string becomes redundant. And because that workaround doesn't always work, I think it's safe to say that we should try not to write code that way. I hope this helped.

At 4:23:35, when the teacher draws our attention to some weird issue, well, let me tell you what the reason is. Simply put, the connection.execute('SQL', (VARIABLES,)) function expects you to pass in the variables in a tuple. In python, you cannot declare a tuple of length one unless you specify it. Two ways to specify that, first is to cast it to the tuple() function, and the other option is to pass in the first item of the tuple and put a single comma (item1,) to indicate a tupple. So, what happens is, when you pass a single item to the tuple and no comma, the () are stripped away and the type of the item gets passed directly.

7:37:00  The JWT token did not expire at all for me regardless of the time value I set. It appears there is no automatic check for expiry time going on. I could make it work by doing the following:

1. Moved the verify_token code block inside get_current_user.
2. Retrieved also the "expire" value from decoded token. If value is none, raise exception. If available then compare it with current time. If current time is greater than the expiry time then it means token is expired , so raise exception. Code block here:

expire = payload.get("expire")
    if expire is None:
        raise credentials_exception
       
    if datetime.now() > datetime.fromtimestamp(expire) :
        raise credentials_exception


Note: I used "datetime.fromtimestamp(expires)" instead of expires directly because earlier in create_access_token, the "expire" value was converted to expire.timestamp() before it was appended/updated to the "to_encode" variable. This was done to fix error "TypeError: Object of type datetime is not JSON serializable"

For those that get an update error after  5:28:00 of a kind: sqlalchemy.exc.IntegrityError: (psycopg2.errors.NotNullViolation) null value in column "id" of relation "posts" violates not-null constraint. For me the problem was that the pydantic Post class had id: Optional[int] which would not be submitted and becomes null in the updated_post, and you cant update id`s with null. My fix was to remove id and created_at from Post class, i think he will do it later himself anyway.

7:06:20 "to_encode" after updated with the "expire" value gave an error for me "TypeError: Object of type datetime is not JSON serializable". I had to add this extra statement: 
expire = expire.timestamp() just before the "to_encode.update" statement. The .timestamp function converts into a string like format that apparently is serializable

At ( 4:21:58 ) : We don't need to explicitly convert the (id) to a string , which is being passed as an argument . The cur.execute() method takes two arguments - 1. A string, which is a SQL query . 2. A tuple, which contains the variables we want to pass into that query. So, in Python we define a tuple with a single element as --> ( id , )  not ( id ) . Here ( id ) is just an integer not a tuple .
Conclusion : Use this instead --> cur.execute( " " "  SELECT * FROM posts WHERE id = %s " " " , ( id , ) )  .This should work fine .

Issue at 10:26:00
The issue seems to lie in inheriting from PostBase (or Post for that matter) from schemas. The issue is fixed when PostOut inherits from BaseModel instead. 
As the response (without response model) returns a Post dictionary and a vote count, it does not have the fields that PostBase requires (title and content are present in the Post dictionary within the response, not within the response directly like vote count). PostBase (or Post) can be used if a new dictionary is defined that includes all the fields that PostBase (or Post) requires.
Also orm_mode need not be set in PostOut as it uses the class Post that has orm_mode set (this is used to import owner information and show it as a dictionary despite it being an object).
Also the fields defined in PostOut must match what the query returns (which can be seen by removing the response model), which is why the field 'Post' must have a capital P (as the model.py contains Post) and why the label for vote count in the query must be the same as the respective field defined in PostOut.

Ok, error fixer KillerFridge is back - the issue you had at 10:25:43 is that originally you built the new schema as PostOut(PostBase) (inheriting from PostBase) not PostOut(BaseModel) (inheriting from BaseModel):

Because PostOut(PostBase) is inheriting from "PostBase" is still expecting to find the "title", "content" etc. fields, which you aren't providing, you have just extended it adding an additional field "Post". When we come back at 10:25.43, you have changed it to inherit "BaseModel" which isn't expecting those fields and so works fine - nothing to do with the capitalisation.

You ask how to constrain the int to be between 0 and 1 at 9:38:00 and it's more simple than you think

 dir: conint(le=1, ge=0)

Hope that helps someone out there!

Guys, if you are interested in how you can validate the dir type for your pydantic Vote model. 

It's as simple as creating an enum

----------------------------------------
eg:

from enum import Enum

class VoteType(int, Enum):
     UP = 1
     DOWN = 0

class Vote(BaseModel):
     post_id: int
     dir: VoteType
----------------------------------------

At 4:24:00  you wonder why you need the extra comma this is because the second argument has to be a sequence (iterable) . A quirk of python is that (id) is not a tuple. To create a tuple you have to do (id,) else it sees it as an int.  Interesting thing is, because it expects an iterable you can use a list  like this ("""SELECT * FROM posts WHERE id=%s""", [id]).fetchone().

09:38:15 So I believe here you could just place bool as the type validation because then if then send 0 it should transform to false or if they do 1 then it should transform to true and vice-versa. So whichever value you wanted can be taken from it.
10:26:10 This error is kind of interesting and I got it as well. I think the best way to go about troubleshooting is to understand that pydantic is going to an error when it isn't provided with sufficient  data as opposed to being provided with too much. After all the response model is meant to cut down the data that is shown to the client. So with this in mind for my schema I made it inherit it from the base model (our imported class) rather than from one of created schema. I think stacking too many schemas put's double the requirements specifically  for the title and content field. One good method to debug this is by inserting in default values into the fields that are causing validation errors as this will create a trail leading you to the issue.
~ 10:15:26 - 10:28:21  more or less here when you group on a column and return columns that are not in the group by nor  being aggregated by a function such as SUM() then you will get an error from SQL. Although I'm not sure why Postgresql didn't return an error. While I was using MS-SQL Server I just did a windowing analytic function such as ...
func.count(models.<insert your orm model>.<insert your column>).over(partition_by=models.<insert your orm model>.<insert your column(group by column)>)).label("<quoi qu'il soit>")

~13:50:00 Around here more or less is where I was having issues connecting to postgres in the container . So What I did was just follow a similar process to what we did for the Ubuntu droplet on digital ocean. So i went into pg_hba and changed some of those settings to md5 and then to be safe in postgres.conf I enabled "*" for the local connections.
Also I had to start the container with the image and then run alembic. Then do docker-compose down and then start it up again.

14:05:00 Here I hadn't been able to log in from the command line nor push any image from docker desktop. So it turns out you can just slightly modify a file in /.docker/config.json just change credsStore to credStore. I'm also using WSL2.

15:10:00 if you start getting errors during the pytests with the traceback involving pydantic you made need this "../.env".
edit: actually it turns out the .env file needs to be in the cwd so that can be for if you decide to enter into a different directory.

For me, it is not about SQL or noSQL
It is more about:
- Is it cheap? is it scaleable? at this stage of the project can I utilize my available resource? 
- Do we need schemaless/no schemaless, usually because of shameless, the database needs to take more space for storing and is slower at execution. Like dynamic-typed langue vs typed language. 
- Can I make relationship ?  (typically the NoSQL is considered weak relationship, BUT YOU CAN STILL MAKE RELATIONSHIP. PLUS, BECAUSE OF SCHEMALESS YOU CAN  EMBED DOCUMENT FOR MAKING THE RELATIONSHIP AND MAKING THE QUERY FASTER WITHOUT JOINING ACROSS TABLES )
- How about its built-in function? it is usually better if you make the computation on the database instead of pulling it down to the server and computing and of course, you don't have to re-develop that function
- The last one, of course, which type of database is more familiar to my team

I just wanted to clarify for everyone that the cause of the problem with the 'Internal server error' is that we establish the connection (and create the channel) as a top-level statement. Kubernetes is smart enough to "find" the new IP when the rabbitmq service is restarted (because it obtains the IP using a DNS lookup), however, since the connection is being established as a top-level statement (basically when the server is started) there is no way for the server to establish a new connection when it brokes (unless it is restarted). RabbitMQ has been built to be used with a single connection by each consumer, thus opening and closing the connection in every request would be even worse. A more reasonable solution would be to check if the connection is healthy (connection.is_open) before using the channel and establish a new connection when it breaks.

RUN apt-get update \

    && pip install --no-cache-dir --upgrade pip

00:00 📝 Overview of Redis

Redis is an in-memory data structure store used as a database, cache, and message broker.
Key features and concepts of Redis include:
Support for various data structures like strings, hashes, sets, lists, sorted sets, bitmaps, hyperlog logs, and geospatial indexes.
Architecture with Redis client and server, supporting master-slave configurations for distributed systems.
Advantages such as speed, with the ability to store the entire dataset in primary memory, asynchronous data persistence, rich data types, and atomic operations.
02:19 🧰 Installing and Starting Redis

Methods to install Redis on different systems, including downloading from the official website, using Docker, or via package managers like apt for Ubuntu.
Commands to start the Redis server and verify its installation status.
04:08 🛠 Basic Operations with Strings in Redis

Demonstrating string commands like SET, GET, GETRANGE, MSET, MGET, STRLEN, RENAME, SETEX, INCR, DECR, INCRBY, DECRBY, SETFLOAT, and EXPIRE.
Explaining how to handle strings, integers, and floating-point values, along with commands for manipulation and expiration.
11:28 📜 Operations with Lists in Redis

Introduction to list data type and commands such as LPUSH, RPUSH, LRANGE, LLEN, LPOP, RPOP, LINSERT, LINDEX, SORT, BLPOP, BRPOP for list manipulation.
Demonstrating list operations including insertion, retrieval, removal, sorting, and blocking operations for queues.
22:09 🧩 Operations with Sets in Redis

Overview of set data type in Redis and commands like SADD, SMEMBERS, SISMEMBER, SCARD, SPOP, SRANDMEMBER, SREM for set manipulation.
Explanation of set operations for managing unique collections and performing set-based operations like union, intersection, difference, and membership checks.
22:26 🛠 Redis Sets Overview

Redis sets allow adding multiple members.
Commands like SADD, SMEMBERS, SCARD, and SISMEMBER are used to manipulate sets efficiently.
29:39 🎯 Redis Sorted Sets Introduction

Redis sorted sets add an extra value (score) to each element, allowing sorting.
Commands like ZADD, ZRANGE, ZCOUNT, and ZREVRANGE are used for sorted set operations.
36:56 🧮 Redis HyperLogLog Data Structure

HyperLogLog is used for probabilistic counting of unique values.
Commands like PFADD, PFCOUNT, and PFMERGE are utilized for HyperLogLog operations.
39:32 🔑 Redis Hashes Overview

Redis hashes store map-like data with string keys and string values.
Commands like HSET, HGET, HDEL, and HLEN are used to manipulate hash data efficiently.
44:10 🔍 Understanding Redis HSTRLEN Command

Explaining how to use the HSTRLEN command to find the length of a field in a hash set.
Demonstrating the usage of HSETNX command to conditionally add fields to a hash set without overriding existing ones.
Highlighting the importance of checking if a value is available before adding it to the hash set.
45:13 🔄 Redis Transactions Overview

Introducing Redis transactions and their role in executing multiple commands atomically.
Explaining the use of MULTI and EXEC commands to start and execute transactions, respectively.
Describing how to discard a transaction using the DISCARD command if needed.
48:32 📢 Redis Pub/Sub Model

Presenting the publisher-subscriber model in Redis for message distribution across channels.
Demonstrating channel subscription and message publication in Redis.
Explaining pattern-based channel subscription and its application in message handling.
54:29 📡 Redis Pub/Sub Commands

Discussing various Pub/Sub commands such as PUBSUB CHANNELS and PUBSUB NUMSUB.
Explaining how to retrieve information about subscribed channels and their subscribers.
Highlighting the distinction between pattern-based and non-pattern-based subscriptions.
56:23 📜 Using Lua Scripts in Redis

Introducing Lua scripting in Redis for executing multiple commands as a single script.
Demonstrating the use of the EVAL command to run Lua scripts in Redis.
Discussing the benefits and considerations of using Lua scripts for complex operations in Redis.
01:05:16 🔒 Redis Connections and Security

Explaining how to check the connection status in Redis using the PING command.
Discussing the concept of databases in Redis and default database assignment.
Introducing basic security measures such as authentication and user access control in Redis.
01:05:56 🗃 Redis Database Selection and Management

Redis allows selecting databases using the SELECT command, with the default database index being zero.
Switching between databases using SELECT affects key uniqueness; keys are unique to each database.
01:07:48 🔐 Redis Client Management and Security

Redis allows listing connected clients with the CLIENT LIST command.
Security measures like setting a password for client authentication are essential for secure Redis access.
01:11:07 🌐 Redis Geospatial Commands

Redis stores geospatial data using longitude and latitude coordinates.
Commands like GEOADD and GEODIST facilitate storing and calculating distances between locations.
01:22:07 ⚙ Redis Benchmarking

Redis provides a built-in benchmarking tool, redis-benchmark, to assess its performance.
Parameters like number of commands, data size, and clients can be adjusted for comprehensive benchmarking.

what is the Library name used for Scripts?

1. mset -> set multiple values for keys
     ex: mset lang Java tech Redis
2. mget -> get multiple values for keys
     ex: mget lang tech
3. strlen -> get length of the key
4. incr -> increment count my 1
5. incrby -> increment count of n
      ex: set count 1
          incr count
          incrby count 10
6. incrbyfloat -> for floating value
7. To expire an value after some seconds
      ex: set a 1
          expire a 10  // here 10 is in seconds
8. flushall command will delete all key, value pairs from redis
9. To push data in a list
      ex: lpush country India
          lpush country US
10. To get all data from ths list
      ex: lrange country 0 -1 (startRange, -1)
11. rpush will push the value to the last index of the list
      ex: rpush country Australia
13. lpop to remove from list 
      ex: lpop country    
14. llen command to get length of the list   
15. lset is to change the object at the index n
      ex: lset country 1 USA
16. linsert is the command to store data at any index
      ex: linsert country before USA "Russia"
17. lindex command get the value from any particular index from list
      ex: lindex country 2
18. sort <list_name> ALPHA to sort list of characters, just sort <list_name> for numbers
      ex: sort country ALPHA

This video was amazing and I absolutely loved it. I also want to say that I took some notes during the course and I think that it will be useful for people who want a recap every once in a while. That said, its still very important to watch this video, in my opinion as I have only a summary of its content. Anyways here you guys go - hope you will find these notes useful!



			      INTERNET

Switch
To connect different computers in an environment together we can use a switch. To connect all the computers to the switch we can use copper wires or fibre optic cables which are faster. Copper wires can be of two types those are CAT-5 and CAT-6. Category 6 is faster than category 5. The switch has ports on them called LAN ports, they are called LAN ports because switches are the ones that help us in creating a LAN.




Access points
Access points are similar to switches but they can be connected to wirelessly.

Once connected with these wires this network forms a LAN(local area network) coz it is located in a specific local area. To send data from PC 1 to PC 6 if they are in a network, the computer creates messages in packets and sends it to the switch. The switch then reads the contents of the packet and understands the destination of the package and sends it to the dest in this case PC6.



How do devices connect to the internet
To create a LAN a switch is fine. But how do devices connect to the internet. For this we use something called a router. The switch is connected to the router with the help of a copper wire. But to actually connect to the internet we use a wire provided by the ISP(internet service provider) for a given price. To send a packet to the internet, the computer first sends it to the switch then the switch sends it to the router and then the router acts like a door to the internet.
Each house or residence will have a LAN. The router helps us in connecting the computer to another computer in the world. In other words the router helps us connect two different LANS together.



What is the internet?
The internet helps connect all the LANs together and creates a network. A home router is very important, it is basically a mix of a router and a switch. This typically also has a access point feature so we can connect to it wirelessly.
So why cant there be just one router and all home routers connect to that router. Well first of all the main router will have to have millions of ports so that each device can connect to it. But the main problem is one router will have to carry all the load making it single point of failure. So in this case if there is a single problem with the router than the internet of the whole world will crash at the same time. Also long cables would be required.


These cables to connect to the internet are even laid down on the ocean floor! If one of these cables are broken it can cause the internet of that continent to break. These are all fibre optic cables coz the speed of data transmission is very high.

Say a computer from India has to send a packet to a computer in Mexico. First the router takes this packet and sends it through cables to another router. This router now has many options to pass this packet forward. To choose the best one it has something called a routing table. The routing table is developed through special algorithms which are created by the processor in the router. It them forwards this packet to the next router based on the routing table. This process of passing the packets is called forwarding. This process repeats until the packet reaches its destination.

One important thing to note is that the router always tries to take the shortest path to reach the dest. This may not be the shortest path visually but taking into account many factors like traffic etc. 
The internet is a network of networks.



Say youtube wants to transmit data to you after you send a request to it. The way it will do this is it will send packets of data to you through the internet. This sending of data piece by piece is called streaming. When we want this packet from youtube, we are actually communicating with high powered computers from youtube called servers. There are many youtube servers distributed around the world to avoid single point of failure.



WAN(Wide area network)
This is to connect two LANs together. You might be wondering then what is the difference between this and the internet. The main difference is privacy.
Assume one LAN network which is an office wants to send data to another Lan network, well if they do this through the internet then the data can be exploited because the internet is public. So if they are in a LAN then only those local computers can access it and if they are in a WAN then only the two connected LAN networks will be able to access the data as it is private.The most popular WAN network method is called VPN(virtual private network). VPN tunnelling provides a tunnel for data transmission in a public network but also gives you anonymity and is more secure. It encrypts your data packets before sending them. People generally use VPN’s to access restricted websites.



How does VPN tunnelling work?
Well the thing is since there really isn’t a physical tunnel connecting the two LAN routers, the data can still be accessed. But the data is put into a secure envelope per say just like you put a letter in an envelope, this data is then encrypted so data cant be hacked or accessed. Putting the data to be transmitted into an envelope or another packet is called encapsulation.



Since the internet is a public network, don’t you think that the data you send to networks like amazon can be hacked?
Well to some extent it can’t be hacked because of something called end to end encryption. In this system only the two communicating users will be able to see the data.



Which is the biggest WAN in the world?
The biggest WAN in the world is the internet itself. But there is a difference between the WAN connection between two offices and the internet. The internet is public and is owned by everyone in the world.


A LAN is more secure than WAN because LAN never passes over the internet but WAN even with VPN passes over the internet.




Public and Private WAN


In a private WAN you can buy a line directly from your ISP and use that private line for connection of networks. This is more secure but it can be very costly especially over long distances. That is why average companies generally prefer Public WANS

We use switches to create a LAN and routers to create a WAN. We cannot use a switch to create a WAN



What is the ISP?
The internet is made up of a connection of many different routers. The routers of the world are connected by these different ISP’s. Each ISP can control specific routers.	 ISP’s are the companies that allow us to connect to the internet. There are many different ISP’s in the world.



LOCAL ISP’S
Local isp’s are responsible for connection of LANS in a locality. These local isps then connect to the regional ISP. So we can say that different local ISPs connect together in a regional ISP. We can say that local isps connect localities like neighbourhoods and Regional ISP’s connect cities in a country. So a network of the country is formed by regional and local ISPs. Global ISPs connects different countries systems together.  

Note : some Local ISP’s can interact with global isps without regional ISPs
Local ISP’s are generally smaller companies and they sometimes may want a direct connection with a global ISP so that there customers can have a better experience

Say a computer in Belgium wants to connect to a website in India but that website has only one server. In this case the user sends a request and the packet moves through the local ISP and regional ISP and global ISP to reach the server of the website. This website then sends the response with all relevant information. The path taken by the request and response can be different as these paths are never fixed. A company like google is very different from this random company. It has servers all around the world, so that its customers can get faster speeds. But sometimes even google faces some slight problems with speed and can dissatisfy its customers. But, google has a good solution for this. This solution is peering.



In peering, googles servers establish a direct connection with our local ISP’s neglecting the need of an ISP infrastructure, This also increases the security.
So we can say that googles fast service speed is because of its distributed servers and peering infrastructure.

It is also possible for us to connect directly to a regional ISP for faster connection.

🎯 Key Takeaways for quick navigation:

00:00 🌐 *Overview of Front-end Development*
- Front-end development involves designing the user interface of websites and apps.
- Front-end developers focus on HTML, CSS, and JavaScript as core technologies.
01:21 🕒 *Duration to Become a Front-end Developer*
- Becoming a front-end developer takes 6 to 12 months for beginners.
- Consistent practice, engagement with the community, and continuous learning are crucial.
02:16 🛣️ *Essential Front-end Technologies*
- HTML, CSS, and JavaScript are fundamental.
- Roadmap emphasizes the ever-evolving nature of technology and the need for continuous learning.
03:12 💻 *Foundational Knowledge*
- Foundational concepts include domains, DNS, servers, and web browser functionality.
- Understanding web development basics is crucial.
03:51 📝 *HTML - Cornerstone of Web Content*
- HTML is the essential structure of web content.
- HTML uses tags to define elements and structure.
04:06 🖥️ *Code Editors - Visual Studio Code*
- Visual Studio Code is a preferred code editor with features like syntax highlighting.
- Code editors enhance the coding experience.
04:33 🎨 *CSS - Aesthetic Appeal of Websites*
- CSS is responsible for the visual appeal of websites.
- It dictates colors, fonts, layouts, and ensures responsiveness.
04:48 🔮 *JavaScript - Adding Interactivity*
- JavaScript adds interactivity to web pages.
- From simple animations to complex functionalities, JavaScript plays a pivotal role.
05:30 🔄 *Version Control Systems - Git and GitHub*
- Git tracks changes and GitHub facilitates collaboration.
- Version control is essential for managing code changes.
06:13 📦 *Package Managers - npm and Yarn*
- Package managers like npm and Yarn manage software libraries and dependencies.
- They ensure the right versions of dependencies for smoother deployment.
06:53 ⚙️ *JavaScript Frameworks and Libraries*
- Frameworks like React, Vue, Angular simplify complex tasks.
- They promote code reusability and enhance performance.
07:46 🛠️ *Build Tools - Vite*
- Build tools like Vite optimize, bundle, and serve code for smooth application performance.
- They handle tasks like transpilation and minification.
08:25 🧪 *JavaScript Testing Tools - Jest and Cypress*
- Testing tools like Jest and Cypress ensure code functions as intended.
- Regular testing minimizes bugs and enhances overall application quality.
08:52 🔄 *TypeScript - A Structured Approach to JavaScript*
- TypeScript introduces static typing for more robust code.
- It helps catch errors during compile time.
09:20 🛡️ *Web Application Security - OWASP*
- Understanding common vulnerabilities and their mitigations is crucial.
- Web application security is a top priority.
09:49 🔄 *GraphQL - Flexible Data Querying*
- GraphQL offers flexibility in querying data.
- It provides a more efficient alternative to traditional REST APIs.
10:18 🚀 *Next.js and Astro - Streamlining Web Development*
- Next.js enhances performance with automatic code splitting and server-side rendering.
- Astro delivers faster websites with less JavaScript by default.
10:47 🚀 *Website Performance Optimization*
- Optimizing images, leveraging browser caching, and minimizing server response times boost website performance.
- Regular audits with tools like Google's Lighthouse provide insights.
11:14 📱 *Cross-platform Mobile Development - React Native*
- React Native allows writing code once and running it on both iOS and Android.
- It offers a rich set of components for native mobile app development.
11:56 🌐 *Continuous Learning in Front-end Development*
- Engaging with the community, experimenting with new tools, and striving for excellence are key.
- The roadmap provides a foundation, but the learning journey in front-end development is endless.

Ignorance is bliss.

Looking at this almost makes it sound easy to learn all these thing. Sure basic HTML and CSS is easy (some could even argue css can be challenging).

Getting into JS is a different story, learning the foundation, the patterns, the pitfalls, learning some framework is far more challenging than it seems and will take easily take years to master.

How to even debug properly, use the dev tools. Accessibility? Did we even mention that?

You also need to learn to collaborate and there's a lot of tooling around that, Figma, Miro, etc.

Then you need to learn the domain you're working in, the business logic. You also need to learn to write clean code and learn to work with other's people code. And how to refactor legacy code.

How to write code that is low coupling with high cohesion? Sounds easy, right? 

Then you need to learn some architecture, how to design a solution, how everything connects together, the different development environments, UAT, preprod, prod, QA. 

Ah right, how are we tracking the code and getting customer feedback? Oh and I forgot, what about the methodology, how to be truly agile.

I didn't even cover how testing can be challenging. How do you debug those tests, how to write meaningful tests. Oh and the metrics.

Then to prepare for interviewing you better know some data structure and algorithms, and be able to communicate your thought process clearly, under pressure.

Many other things I'm not even talking about and some I barely scratched the surface. Did I even mention security? 

Being a developer is a bumpy road and it's extremely challenging. Everything you learn now will be outdated in a couple year so better focus on the foundation. But still, there's just so much to know and it's always evolving.

Good luck with all that, hope you get good seniors to guide you gently and not some hardcore PMs with impossible deadlines!

Complete roadmap:

*1. How internet works:*

-Domain 
-Domain name systems
-Servers
-Protocols
-Role of browsers and how they render web pages

*2. knowledge of VScode*

*3. HTML, CSS and JS fundamentals*

*4. Prompt engineering*

*5. git and GitHub*

*6. Package managers(NPM and yarn* 

-Package managers are used to manage and update libraries

*7. Bootstrap*

-Bootstrap allows responsiveness to the website

*8.Sass is a CSS framework that enhances the styling process*

*9. REACT/ANGULAR AND VUE for scalability and maintenance* 

*10: Tailwind CSS is used to produce custom designs*

*11. BYTE*

*12. Jest(Unit testing) and Cypress(end-to-end testing)*

*13. Typescript(helps catch errors in code)*

*14. OWASP(for security)*

*15.GraphQL(fetches data)*

*16. NEXT.js(enhances performance and developer experience)

*17. Astro(building faster websites*

*18. Google Lighthouse*

*19. REACT Native*

I'm sorry but this is not a roadmap. It's more of an overview of what's out there with a rough order in which to learn each thing. A roadmap would be more like this:
1. learn HTML and CSS
2. learn some JavaScript
3. learn git 
4. build some projects, use git, deploy to web
5. learn DOM manipulation and async JavaScript
6. build more projects
7. pick some CSS preprocessor and/or framework and build some projects
8. pick a JS framework, build some projects
9. learn a state management framework for that framework from point 8., build some projects
10. learn some databases
11. build a project that looks and feels like a real world app, learn anything else that is needed for this project, then repeat

If you're a beginner, listen up: I've finished Dave's HTML video which was awesome for beginners cause he explained every step along the way! Then I started this one. I'm 4 hours in with 7 hours to go, I have to say that things start to get a bit different. Some random css thrown in without saying why and I watch some of the same sections twice to see if I missed anything but no I didn't miss anything. This style specifically makes it really hard to continue to learn this way. Like units, sizes, flexbox, grid layout  def need a more in-depth touch if this is going to serve to the beginners without the need to switch to other resources like ChatGPT. 

For example: I'm asking ChatGPT why we use: 
justify-content: center;
align-items: center;
in the same place. As there is no explanations for it in the course as a beginner expects one so I constantly stop the video and go on ChatGPT to clarify any confusion and so a complete beginner should not expect to learn the fundamentals of css here even if this is a 11-hour video cause as you continue "but why" questions will clutter your mind.

This might be a GREAT REFRESHER for people who already learned and kind a need to refresh their knowledge but as a new beginner - especially for some sections - a more in depth look would have done wonders. Maybe if there was one website to go with it to build on top of each other and enough practice materials that would have been great. 

As a free resource I do understand the amount of effort behind this video, I appreciate it but from a beginners perspective - we need to elarn faster hence the existence of AI - I think I will need to look elsewhere to better understand CSS with more visuals and more emphasis on the WHY rather than just what it does, cause there will come a time where we will need to know why we use a specific css over another. I might change my comment as I am not ready to give up yet but I hope it gets better from a learner's point.

It blows my mind how far HTML and CSS have come. I started teaching myself about web design in the early 90s. Right click> view source. I would spend hours pouring over notepad screens tweaking and modifying other people's HTML. Eventually, I was writing my own from scratch.

Then, one day, I came across one that had the CSS tags in the header. Back then, CSS was just an easy way to change the colors and fonts of every page on a site by changing one file. It made things so much easier.

It still does that but now it does _so much_ more. Browsers are so much more sophisticated than IE and Netscape Navigator 3.

I didn't keep up with it. I stopped learning in the early aughts when I was tinkering with Macromedia Flash and Actionscript. This course is exactly what I've been looking for to get me back up to speed with CSS. I'm bookmarking this video to use as a reference.

Only when you have learnt about the basics proceed to this lecture else you might take little bit more time thats all.

All the best to those who are learning this

3 days after its release, this video was my introduction to web development. 2 weeks ago I started my first job as a full stack developer. Work hard and never give up!

Edit almost 2 years after:
*For the skeptics*
I was really ecstatic when I made this comment so I might have overlooked a few things. I see some of you did not believe me, and I think it is good to be skeptic about things you read on the internet. However, the comment was true. Seven months after my first line of code, I was hired as a full stack developer at age 21.
Now the caveats. 
Number 1: I am a physics dropout so you could say I had a math and problem-solving background. However, I wasn't really good at physics, that's why I dropped out to be a dev.
Number 2: when I said "work hard and never give up"(in retrospect it sounds super corny), I really mean it. I was full blown 8-10 hours a day learning to code. Even most weekends. I missed going out with my friends or going o vacation or whatever. Also, I had the privilege of having that time, as I was studying and living with my parents. And also, I kind of gambled here, because I dropped out without telling my parents, so if I failed I would have lost a full year of college which was very risky and they wouldn't have been very proud.
Number 3: Today the job market is more difficult than 2 years ago. However, don't get disappointed as those things tend to be cyclic and it should get better.
So to conclude I would say that maybe depending on your situation and how much dedication you want to put to it, you may be able to land a job after 1-1.5 years of studying

*For the ones who want resources*
Many asked for resources and roadmaps
I recommend 2 things that were useful for me. Firstly, as you did in this tutorial, build projects. Even if they are fully copied from another person. It will help you understand.
Also, now I will give you a mini roadmap. It will be order, but if you get bored of something, you may skip it and return afterwards. You might not grasp fully concepts when you skip something important, but it is better to be a bit confused but entertained than to call it quits.
Google any concept you don't understand
0. Learn git. Very important.
1. Fully understand javascript and ES6 as much as possible. 
2. Get into the basics of react, node and express and build some small projects where you consume REST APIs from a React SPA. You should eventually learn to use a react state manager such as redux or zustand.
3. Learn a database. I started with MongoDB which is quite good and free to deploy in MongoAtlas. You can use the mongoose ORM to interact with the DB from nodejs. I recommend you eventually learn SQL though as it is really powerful (I recommend PostgreSQL)
4. Learn TypeScript. Do not skip this, it is extremely important
5. Learn authentication via JWT in express.
6. Learn the Next.js framework.
7. Learn to deploy on Netlify and Vercel for free.
8. Build an app that will look good on your resume, try to make it something useful.
9. Learn websockets. How to communicate with socketio from node to react.
10. This is no longer programming, but build a good CV, search how to make it pass ATS, make it eyecatching, highlight your skills and apps you made. I didn't but you can make a portfolio. Definitely make a LinkedIn account and connect with other tech people. Have an appropriate picture, add your skills and education or work experience if you have it.
11. Study leetcode. You will probably get some programming challenges in your job interviews so be prepared. Also learn soft skills you can use for non technical questions you will be asked in the interview
12. Learn Agile Methodologies such as SCRUM and learn to use JIRA(recruiters will love that, I promise)
Now you're ready to start applying to everything. I applied to about 50 jobs and got 2 interviews. In both I did really good. You will get few chances with no experience, so do not waste them.
While you're looking for a job, you can learn more really useful technologies. I recommend Docker, GraphQL, basic AWS, nginx, Nest.js, React Native, maybe other framework other than react or other language other than javascript. But, more importantly get deeper knowledge of everything you learned before.

I can't handle resources on here because can't post urls on yt comments. However, if you want to ask me for resources or anything about programming, DM me at instagram, i'm grego_kun.
Happy coding!

Here's an interesting tip:
Once you've learned how to use the 'onclick' property with the button element, why not create a temporary button  on your app specifically for control-logging anything you need to debug.  You can create a function in JS and have console.log() inside of it. Link that to your button, and then whenever you need to console log something, like in the exercises for example, you can just enter the required variable inside console.log() within your function, and then click the button on your app, and, VOILA, console-logged!  

It's not necessary but it's a nice touch and then you won't have to keep on typing out console.log() for each exercise.  It's also a fun exercise in itself.  You can always remove the button later when your app is complete.

Here are some extra smart tips on prompt engineering that are practical:

- Embrace the Socratic method: Instead of asking direct questions, break down your prompts into a series of leading questions that guide the model towards the desired output.

- Leverage few-shot learning: Provide a few examples of the desired input-output pairs before the actual prompt. This can significantly improve the model's understanding and performance.

- Employ recursive re-writing: Feed the model's output back into itself as a new prompt, allowing it to iteratively refine and improve its responses.

- Utilize prompt chaining: Break down complex tasks into a sequence of smaller prompts, where the output of one prompt becomes the input for the next.

- Explore prompt augmentation: Supplement your prompts with additional context, such as relevant background information, constraints, or examples of what not to do.

- Experiment with prompt ensembling: Combine the outputs of multiple prompts or models to create a more robust and diverse final output.

- Leverage prompt-based fine-tuning: Fine-tune language models on a small dataset of prompts and desired outputs, tailoring them for specific tasks or domains.

- Incorporate prompt-based retrieval: Use prompts to query and retrieve relevant information from external sources, effectively augmenting the model's knowledge.

- Explore prompt-based translation: Translate prompts into different languages or styles, potentially unlocking new perspectives or capabilities.

- Leverage prompt-based reasoning: Guide the model to perform multi-step reasoning or problem-solving by breaking down complex tasks into a series of prompts.

No. Prompt engineering almost 100% of the time is about the dynamic creation of prompts that tune prompts to specific applications.  It is almost never about just typing text into ChatGPT better or making great prompts one at a time. Nobody I know is hiring people to do that.  The engineering part of this is application development that takes  user input in an application and then dynamically creates prompts using other data.... like customer specific information  For example,  a prompt engineer may be asked to upgrade a CRM application so that when the user asks a question, it takes previous purchases and uses that data to create a prompt to pass along to ChatGPT 4.  That is prompt engineering. Too many people miss the importance of the dynamic nature of prompts and think of it as an end user using ChatGPT .  That isn't what it is about at all.

It's a good video but it really misses what companies desire when it comes to "Prompt Engineering".  Nobody wants to hire someone that can type in good prompts. That isn't what it is at all.  Prompt engineering is what you are seeing in all the AI tools that use ChatGPT 4  API or API's for other tools to "engineer" prompts that can can be integrated into applications.   For example a company like AT&T might hire a prompt engineer that will take user input from a chat and then wrap that input with appropriate domain knowledge and context.    A company making a language learning application might want to hire a prompt engineer to design prompts that take the level of the student, the language they are learning, their previous history in using the application, and then create prompts that will take users to the next level.

This video I think completely misses the context for what prompt engineering means as it relates to employable opportunities.  You need to know how to use the API and construct prompts programatically using domain specific knowledge.
